nd, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salway","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Salewi</i>, <i>Selawy</i>, probably from Old English <i>Sǣlwīg</i> (<i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wīg</i> ‘battle’). The name may sometimes have been confused with   Selwyn  .","Americanized form of French   Salois  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Selway","meanings":["English (Somerset and Devon): variant of   Salway  ."]},{"name":"Soloway","meanings":["English: variant of   Salway  .","Americanized form of Jewish, Ukrainian, or Belorussian   Solovey   ‘nightingale’."]},{"name":"Selwyn","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire):","from the Middle English personal name <i>Selewin(e)</i> (Old English <i>Selewine</i>, perhaps from <i>sele</i> ‘hall’ or <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, prosperity’ + <i>wine</i> ‘friend’).","of Norman origin, perhaps from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Selvein</i>, <i>Silvein</i> (from Latin <i>Silvanus</i>, an adjective from <i>silva</i> ‘woodland’), with vocalization of /v/ to /w/, possibly through influence of the name above. In Anglo-Norman usage both <i>Selvein</i> and <i>Silvester</i> were sometimes Latinized as <i>Salvagius</i> ‘wild, savage’ (see   Sylvester   and   Savage  ), though whether the vernacular surnames were ever interchangeable is a question for further research."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Salway was born in 1270, in Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Saleway, was 40 and his mother, Saleway, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Richard Salway. He died in 1307, in England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Décédée","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","England":"Angleterre","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Salway est né en 1270, à Cannock, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William Saleway, avait 40 ans et sa mère, Saleway, avait 20 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Richard Salway. Il est décédé en 1307, à Angleterre, à l’âge de 37 ans."},"de":{"1270–1307":"1270–1307","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1275–Female":"1275–Verstorben","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","England":"England","Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cannock, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Als Richard S